        <encodingDesc xml:lang="en" xml:id="encodingDesc">
            <samplingDecl xml:lang="en" change="#d2e380" xml:id="samplingDecl_1.d2e68">
                <p xml:lang="en" change="#d2e380" xml:id="p_2.d2e70">The edition is based on the digital transcripts (HTML files wrapped in ePub) available from <ref target="http://shamela.ws/index.php/book/29676" xml:lang="en" change="#d2e380" xml:id="ref_1.d2e72"><foreign xml:lang="ar-Latn-x-ijmes" change="#d2e380" xml:id="foreign_1.d2e73">al-maktabat al-shāmila</foreign></ref>.</p>
            </samplingDecl>
            <editorialDecl xml:lang="en" change="#d2e380" xml:id="editorialDecl_1.d2e78">
                <p xml:lang="en" change="#d2e380" xml:id="p_3.d2e80">The original editorial practices followed by <ref target="http://shamela.ws/index.php/book/29676" xml:lang="en" change="#d2e380" xml:id="ref_2.d2e82"><foreign xml:lang="ar-Latn-x-ijmes" change="#d2e380" xml:id="foreign_2.d2e83">al-maktabat al-shāmila</foreign></ref>can only be deduced from the limited mark-up found in the digital text provided online and as ePub. It appears from that that paragraphs and head lines were recorded and preserved. They also recorded page breaks, but they do not generally correspond to the page breaks in the print edition and were thus marked with <att xml:lang="en" change="#d2e380" xml:id="att_1.d2e86">ed</att>="shamela"</p>
                <p xml:lang="en" change="#d2e380" xml:id="p_4.d2e90">After reviewing the image files and the official publication schedule, the dates provided as <foreign xml:lang="ar-Latn-x-ijmes" change="#d2e380" xml:id="foreign_3.d2e92">hijrī</foreign> seem to be correct</p>
                <p xml:lang="en" change="#d2e380" xml:id="p_5.d2e96">Some phenomena have been marked in red spans by <ref target="http://shamela.ws/index.php/book/29676" xml:lang="en" change="#d2e380" xml:id="ref_3.d2e98"><foreign xml:lang="ar-Latn-x-ijmes" change="#d2e380" xml:id="foreign_4.d2e99">al-maktabat al-shāmila</foreign></ref>. Red spans that contained three points only were considered indicators of ellipses and transformed into <tag xml:lang="en" change="#d2e380" xml:id="tag_1.d2e102">gap resp="#org_MS"</tag>. Upon further scrutiny, it turned out that most, if not all, of these <gi xml:lang="en" change="#d2e380" xml:id="gi_1.d2e105">gap</gi>s indicated the division between two halfs of the line of a <foreign xml:lang="ar-Latn-x-ijmes" change="#d2e380" xml:id="foreign_5.d2e108">qaṣīda</foreign>. I have converted all <gi xml:lang="en" change="#d2e380" xml:id="gi_2.d2e111">p</gi>s that contained two short lines of text divided by <gi xml:lang="en" change="#d2e380" xml:id="gi_3.d2e115">gap</gi> into <gi xml:lang="en" change="#d2e380" xml:id="gi_4.d2e118">l</gi> of <att xml:lang="en" change="#d2e380" xml:id="att_2.d2e121">type</att>="bayt" with <gi xml:lang="en" change="#d2e380" xml:id="gi_5.d2e124">seg</gi> child elements. All other red spans have been rendered as <gi xml:lang="en" change="#d2e380" xml:id="gi_6.d2e127">gap</gi>.</p>
            </editorialDecl>
